  "text": "will reduce the tension between the organization and its social environment to decrease the costs of group membership. Organizations may selectively adapt, changing specific tensionrelated characteristics, while maintaining others, as described by Iannaccone [CITATION_1] (Iannaccone : 1203 . This study indicates that religious organizations not only selectively choose what characteristics they adapt, but also how they self- the religious practice tends towards the church spectrum. However, the lower the extent to which outsiders can gain access to the religious practice, the higher the degrees of freedom to drift towards the sect spectrum. As a result, \"sect\" and \"church\" may simultaneously co-exist within the same religious organization, while being selectively performed in specific spaces and times.",
